# React & UI implementation rules

This rule defines React and UI implementation conventions.

The visual source of truth is defined in:
`.cursor/rules/ui-kit-source-of-truth.mdc`

Do not use this rule as a design-system override.

## Components

- Use functional React components.
- Prefer composition over local forks.
- Reuse primitives from `src/components/ui/*` before creating custom markup.
- Reuse shared product patterns from `src/components/shared/*` when available.
- Type business props from `src/types/odcs.ts`; do not duplicate business types.
- Use hooks for reusable logic.

## Business constraints

- Respect `isLocked` on every editable field.
- Published, deprecated, retired, and otherwise locked contracts must stay read-only.
- Users with the `viewer` role must never edit contract content.
- Destructive actions must use `ConfirmDialog`.
- User feedback must go through `useToast`.

## Styling

- Use Tailwind classes.
- Prefer theme tokens from `src/index.css` (`neutral-*`, `blue-*`, `green-*`, `red-*`, `orange-*`, etc.).
- Avoid arbitrary hex colors in product UI unless explicitly approved.
- Avoid local badge, chip, pill, button, tab, input, table, avatar, or empty-state forks.
- Keep schema and governance tables dense and compact, but do not hardcode layout values that conflict with the UI Kit.
- Do not use this rule to define lifecycle colors, badge sizing, or component variants; follow the UI Kit source-of-truth rule instead.

## Imports

- Prefer aliases: `@/components/...`, `@/lib/...`, `@/types/...`.
- Use `lucide-react` for icons.

## Before creating custom UI

Check, in order:

1. `src/components/ui/*`
2. `src/components/shared/*`
3. `src/pages/ComponentsPage.tsx`

If a pattern already exists, reuse it instead of recreating it.
If a pattern appears missing from the UI Kit, report the gap before adding a new local implementation.

## Example - locking editable fields

```tsx
// Correct: editable fields respect isLocked.
<Input value={col.logicalName} disabled={isLocked} onChange={...} />

// Incorrect: a published or viewer-locked contract can still be edited.
<Input value={col.logicalName} onChange={...} />
```
